\par }\pard \ql \li3030\ri331\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin3030\itap0 {\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 interlocutory matter; s 54 Limitation Act \endash 
 whether email constitutes written and signed acknowledgement for the purposes of s 54 Limitation Act)
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri331\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 1\tab }{\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 MASTER:}{\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
  By amended summons filed 28 August 2003 the plaintiff seeks firstly an order that the time for filing this amended summons be extended pursuant to Part 51B r 5(5) of the }{\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Supreme Court Rules (SCR)}{
\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 ; secondly, an order that the plaintiff be granted leave to appeal the decision of B A Lulham, Local Court Magistrate
 dated 28 May 2003 pursuant to Part 51B of the SCR;  thirdly, an order pursuant to s 109 of the }{\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Justices Act}{\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  1902 (NSW) and/or s 69(4) of the }{
\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Local Court (Civil Claims) Act }{\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 1970 (NSW) quashing the order of Lulham LCM dismissing the plaintiff\rquote s (defendant i
n local court proceedings) application that the defendant\rquote s (plaintiff in local court proceedings) statement of claim be dismissed on the basis that the defendant\rquote s alleged cause of action was statute barred under s 14(1) of the }{
\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Limitation Act}{\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  1969 (NSW) (
the Act);  fourthly, a declaration that the Magistrate erred in law in his interpretation of s 54 of the Act;  fifthly, a declaration that the Magistrate erred in law in finding that there had been a confirmation of the defendant\rquote 
s cause of action pursuant to s 54(2)(a)(i) of the Act;  sixthly, a declaration that the Magistrate erred in law in finding that there had been a written and signed acknowledgement of the defendant\rquote 
s cause of action by the plaintiff pursuant to s 54(4) of the Act;  seventhly, a declaration that the Magistrate erred in law in his interpretation of s 9 of the }{\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Electronic Transaction Act}{
\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  2000 (NSW);  and eighthly, an order pursuant to s 109 of the }{\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Justices Act}{\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  or s 69 of the }{
\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Local Court (Civil Claims) Act}{\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  or part 51B r 5(6) that the defendant\rquote 
s (plaintiff below) cause of action in matter No 11376 of 2002 in the Downing Centre Local Court be dismissed with costs.
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri331\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 2\tab By notice of motion filed 23 June 2003 the defendant (in these proceedings) seeks an order that summary judgment be entered 
against the plaintiff as claimed in the Local Court on the grounds that there is no defence to the claim made by the defendant.  The plaintiff relied on her affidavits both sworn 4 August 2003.  The defendant relied on his affidavit sworn 16 June 2003.  F
or convenience, I shall refer to Ms Kim Therese McGuren the plaintiff in these proceedings as Ms McGuren and Mr Robert John Simpson the defendant in these proceedings as Mr Simpson.  This matter has been referred to a Master for hearing by the list Judge.

\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \ql \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Grounds of appeal
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri331\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 3\tab 
The plaintiff appeals the whole of the decision of Lulham LCM dated 28 May 2003.  The grounds of appeal are that firstly, the Magistrate erred in holding that the plaintiff, after limitation fixed by or under the Act in respect of the defendant\rquote 
s cause of action had commenced to run, but before the expiration of the limitation period, confirmed the cause of action, such that the defendant\rquote s alleged cause of action was not statute barred under s 14(1) of the Act; secondly, the Magistrate
 erred in finding that an email dated 29 September 1999 (the email) which the defendant relied on was a confirmation of a cause of action by the plaintiff pursuant to s 54(2)(a)(i) of the Act;  thirdly, the Magistrate erred in law in holding that the said
 
email amounted to an acknowledgement by the plaintiff of the cause of action to the defendant for the purposes of s 54(2)(a)(i) of the Act;  fourthly, the Magistrate erred in law in holding that the said email amounted to a written and signed acknowledgme
nt of the defendant\rquote s cause of action by the plaintiff pursuant to s 54(4) of the Act;  fifthly, the Magistrate further erred in law in holding that s 9 of the }{\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Electronic Transaction Act}{
\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  applied, as that Act was not in force at the time that the email was s
ent, did not have any express or retrospective operation and did not operate retrospectively so as to alter substantive rights in the manner in which the Magistrate applied;  and sixthly, the Magistrate failed to have regard to relevant factors and took i
nto account irrelevant factors giving rise to an error in accordance with the principles in }{\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 House v The King}{\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
 (1936) 55 CLR 499 at 505, and further that the Magistrate\rquote s decision in declining to hold that the defendant\rquote s cause of action in the proceedings below were statute barred under s 14(1) of the Act was \'93unreasonable or plainly unjust\'94
 and a \'93substantial wrong\'94 occurred in such a way as to demonstrate error in exercising the discretion in accordance with }{\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 House}{\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
.  Ms McGuren the appellant, was the defendant in the Local Court.  Mr Simpson the defendant in these proceedings was the plaintiff in the Local Court.  
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri331\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 4\tab 
On 28 May 2003, the Magistrate held that the email forwarded by the defendant to the plaintiff complied with the requirements of s 54 of the Act and the plaintiff was entitled to maintain these proceedings.
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \ql \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Whether leave to appeal should be granted
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri331\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 5\tab Section 69(2B) of the }{\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Local Courts (Civil Claims) Act}{
\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  provides that an appeal against an interlocutory order does not lie to this Court except by 
leave.  The plaintiff has advanced four reasons why leave ought to be granted.  They are firstly, the questions of law, if determined in favour of the plaintiff, will dispose of the entire proceedings in the Local Court;  secondly, the questions of law de
pend on the construction of the email and the two statutes in question and not on disputed facts;  thirdly, the plaintiff should not be exposed to the costs and burden of a full trial in the Local Court if the defendant\rquote 
s action is doomed to failure;  and f
ourthly, the question whether, at common law, an email is a writing signed by the maker within s 54(4) of the Act is an important one with significance beyond the parties to this case.  The defendant submitted that leave ought not be granted.
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri331\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 6\tab As the limitation decision has finally determined the rights of the parties, this interlocutory appeal should be entertained \endash 
 see }{\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Itek Graphix Pty Ltd v Elliott}{\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  (2002) 54 NSWLR 207;  [2002] NSWCA 104.  Thus leave to appeal is granted.
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \ql \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Alleged errors of law
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri331\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 7\tab 
The defendant submitted that the Magistrate did not make any errors of law.  The defendant submitted that if any error were made, they amounted to errors of fact and were thus not appealable.  Both parties referred to }{
\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Collector of Customs v Agfa-Gevaert Ltd}{\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  (1996) 186 CLR 389 at 395 where the High Court referred to the Full Federal Court decision of }{
\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Collector of Customs v Pozzolanic Enterprises Pty Ltd}{\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033  (1993) 43 FCR 280 at 287 where the Court identified five propositions, they are:
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \qj \li2160\ri1051\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin1051\lin2160\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 \'931.\tab The question whether
 a word or phrase in a statute is to be given its ordinary meaning or some technical or other meaning is a question of law.
\par 
\par 2.\tab The ordinary meaning of a word or its non-legal technical meaning is a question of fact.
\par 
\par 3.\tab The meaning of a technical legal term is a question of law.
\par 
\par 4.\tab The effect or construction of a term whose meaning or interpretation is established is a question of law.
\par 
\par 5.\tab The question whether facts fully found fall within the provision of a statutory enactment properly construed is generally a question of law.\'94
\par 
\par }\pard \qj \li1440\ri1051\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin1051\lin1440\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 In }{\i\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Pozzolanic,}{\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
 the Full Court qualified the fifth proposition.  The Court said that, when a statute uses words according to their ordinary meaning and it is reasonably open to hold that the facts of the case fall within those word
s, the question as to whether they do or do not is one of fact.\'94
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \ql \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The statutory framework \endash  the pleadings
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\b\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri331\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 8\tab The statement of claim pleads:
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \qj \li1440\ri1051\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin1051\lin1440\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 \'93The plaintiff claims the sum of $23,000 plus interest of $21,208.21 in respect of the following cause of action;
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \qj \fi-720\li2160\ri1051\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin1051\lin2160\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 1.\tab 
The plaintiff claims payment from the defendant for compensation cheque payment on a motor vehicle payable to the plaintiff and which the defendant refused to give to the plaintiff.
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \qj \fi-720\li2160\ri1051\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin1051\lin2160\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 2.\tab The cheque was given by the plaintiff to the defendant at Long Bay 
Goal whilst the plaintiff was on remand on 26 November 1993.
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \qj \fi-720\li2160\ri1051\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin1051\lin2160\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 3.\tab The defendant has last acknowledged in writing by email the above monies on 29 September 1999.\'94
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri331\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 9\tab Mr Simpson appeared in the Local Court in person.  Counsel represented Ms McGuren.  The Magi
strate defined the issues in dispute as being that Mr Simpson and Ms McGuren were in a de facto relationship between 1992 and 2000.  Mr Simpson\rquote 
s case is that he was in gaol in November 1993 when he received a cheque from solicitors being the net proceeds 
of a claim for damages for personal injuries he suffered in a motor vehicle accident.  The cheque was for $23,000.  He endorsed the cheque in favour of Jody McGuren, Ms McGuren\rquote 
s sister, to enable Jody McGuren to bank the cheque in her account on behalf of Ms McGuren who did not wish to bank the cheque in her account as she was receiving AusStudy while studying Law in Queensland.  Mr Simpson\rquote 
s case is that the defendant used the money almost entirely for her own purposes and he seeks recovery of the money from Ms McGuren.  Ms McGuren\rquote 
s case is that she used the money in accordance with instructions from Mr Simpson towards payments on his account and on other amounts following discussion and with the approval of Mr Simpson.  Ms McGuren is a solicitor. 
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri331\sl240\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 10\tab On behalf of Ms McGuren it was submitted that the proceedings were statute barred pursuant to s 14(1) of the Act.  As Mr Simpson
\rquote s cause of action arose on 26 November 1993, he was required to commence the proceedings by 25 November 1999.  The statement of claim was filed on 26 August 2002. Thus Mr Simpson\rquote 
s claim is statute barred unless his case falls within s 54 of the Act.  
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri331\sl360\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\rin331\lin720\itap0 {\f0\fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
